JAMstack_conf live broadcast eclipses viewership of Sox title win.

By Anthony Castrovince MLB.com @castrovince
an hour ago

LOS ANGELES -- The baseball season ends just as the discussion about this Boston Red Sox club's place in the sport's long and layered history begins. It's not enough to simply state the simple story, which is that the Red Sox put the finishing touches on their ninth title -- and their fourth since 2004 -- with a clear-and-convincing 5-1 victory over the Dodgers in Game 5 of the World Series on Sunday night at Dodger Stadium.

• Get World Series champs gear

View Full Game Coverage

LOS ANGELES -- The baseball season ends just as the discussion about this Boston Red Sox club's place in the sport's long and layered history begins. It's not enough to simply state the simple story, which is that the Red Sox put the finishing touches on their ninth title -- and their fourth since 2004 -- with a clear-and-convincing 5-1 victory over the Dodgers in Game 5 of the World Series on Sunday night at Dodger Stadium.

• Get World Series champs gear

View Full Game Coverage

Game Date Results Highlights
Gm 1 Oct. 23 BOS 8, LAD 4 Watch
Gm 2 Oct. 24 BOS 4, LAD 2 Watch
Gm 3 Oct. 26 LAD 3, BOS 2 (18) Watch
Gm 4 Oct. 27 BOS 9, LAD 6 Watch
Gm 5 Oct. 28 BOS 5, LAD 1 Watch
Shop for postseason gear: Dodgers | Red Sox
• Complete World Series coverage

No, a team this talented, a march this methodical deserves a deeper appreciation. The Red Sox began 2018 by blowing an eighth-inning Opening Day lead and sending their fans into a Twitter tizzy. Then they won 119 times in all -- a mark bested only by the 1998 Yankees (125) and the 2001 Mariners (120). The Red Sox needed just one game north of the minimum each to take down the 100-win Yankees in the American League Division Series, the defending World Series champion Astros in the AL Championship Series and the two-time National League champion Dodgers in the Fall Classic.

"It's amazing," said Mookie Betts. "This is why we play the game, to win a World Series. And to do it this year, with this group of guys, is a blessing."

Their solitary setback in this best-of-seven World Series was the 18-inning extravaganza that was Friday's Game 3. To repeat: It took the equivalent of two baseball games to beat these Red Sox. And even in the wake of that lone loss, there was a standing ovation in Boston's clubhouse for Nathan Eovaldi's outrageous relief effort -- another signal of the closeness, camaraderie and confidence that carried this club to glory.

Glory arrived on a Southern California night in front of a crowd littered with some untold-but-notable number of red shirts breaking up the blue in the stands.

• Pearce joins ranks of unlikely World Series heroes

It arrived behind the short-rested but no-less-effective arm of David Price, who had already shaken off his October blues and was now back to cementing his Boston legend with seven-plus magnificent innings in which he was touched up only by a first-inning homer from a familiar Series source in David Freese. It arrived with a trio of damaging dingers against Clayton Kershaw -- the two-run blast belted World Series MVP Steve Pearce in the first, the solo homer that snapped Betts' cold spell in the sixth and the center-field swat delivered by J.D. Martinez in the seventh. Pearce's second shot, off Pedro Baez in the eighth, was a resounding capper to a breakout postseason for the veteran journeyman.

• Pearce named World Series MVP

This was a bit of a tensionless tilt -- one polished off with Chris Sale's perfect ninth.

These two franchises had not met on the Series stage in 102 years, but you know what they say about the past informing the present. The 1916 Red Sox, colorfully characterized by one New York Times account from the time as "the carmine-hosed Boston warriors," took Games 1 and 2 at home, were defeated in the first road tilt, erased a deficit to win Game 4 and then finished the Series off in Game 5.

"This is why you're in the game," said president of baseball operations Dave Dombrowski. "It's the best feeling you can possibly have from a professional perspective, and sometimes you wonder if it's ever going to happen again. We've been close a lot of times. It's the best feeling you can possibly have, and we have people here from the whole organization, ownership here, they've been so supportive of the team. I've been fortunate, my family is here, too. It's just as good as it gets."

• Perfect ending for near-perfect Red Sox

"Had a great run," said Dodgers third baseman Justin Turner. "We're one of the last two teams playing, and we fell a little short again. We did things people didn't even think we would accomplish. Back-to-back years falling short in the World Series is brutal, but [we've] just got to try to hang our hats on all the good things we accomplished this year."

If the long-ago result is replicated in the modern day, then the description fits, too. But even in Red Sox lore, which of course includes a 2004 team that killed a curse and captured imaginations well outside the borders of Red Sox Nation, this 2018 squad has a special, perhaps singular, place to claim. Sunday's Series finale -- a game that, to once again borrow a vibrant line from the Times circa 1916, "resembled a tug of war between an elephant and a goldfish" -- only confirmed it.

MOMENTS THAT MATTERED
Freese frame: As if the sight of Freese homering in a World Series game hadn't already evoked memories of Game 6 in 2011, in the third inning he tripled on a fly ball that was misplayed by the right fielder. In '11, it was Nelson Cruz. On this night, it was Martinez, who simply lost the ball in the L.A. haze. With Freese on third and one out, Price was in a bit of a bind, but he got Turner to ground out on the first pitch. And when Enrique Hernandez sent another fly ball to right, Martinez made the catch in foul territory to end the threat. When he got back in the dugout, Price made it a point to give Martinez the ol' Bash Brothers forearm bump -- a nice show of appreciation between two teammates.

SOUND SMART
Alex Cora became just the fifth manager to win the World Series as a rookie skipper, joining Bucky Harris (1924 Senators), Eddie Dyer (1946 Cardinals), Ralph Houk (1961 Yankees) and Bob Brenly (2001 D-backs).

This game marked just the second time in World Series history that both teams homered in the first inning. The other was Game 5 in 1948, between the Boston Braves and the Indians (Bob Elliott and Dale Mitchell).

Pearce became, per the Elias Sports Bureau, the first position player to be named World Series MVP with 50 or fewer regular-season games for the winning team in his career (at the time of the Fall Classic) and just the second midseason acquisition to win the honor, joining Donn Clendenon of the 1969 Mets.

Freese has now hit both a leadoff homer and a walk-off homer (Game 6, 2011) in the World Series. The only other player with both is Derek Jeter. Freese now has twice as many career games with both a homer and a triple in the World Series (two) as he does in the regular season (one).

Anthony Castrovince has been a reporter for MLB.com since 2004. Read his columns, listen to his podcast and follow him on Twitter at @Castrovince.

Pearce rides midseason trade to Series MVP

By Anthony Castrovince MLB.com @castrovince
30 minutes ago

LOS ANGELES -- One more phone call came with the news of one more pending move for Steve Pearce, whose unsettled existence in the course of a meandering Major League path had become par for his convoluted course.

Pearce had just returned to the Blue Jays after six weeks spent rehabbing an oblique injury, and he had just welcomed his wife and daughter to Toronto for some long-awaited family time during a long homestand. So Blue Jays general manager Ross Atkins' call informing him that he had been dealt to the Red Sox was politely but perhaps not altogether warmly received.

View Full Game Coverage

LOS ANGELES -- One more phone call came with the news of one more pending move for Steve Pearce, whose unsettled existence in the course of a meandering Major League path had become par for his convoluted course.

Pearce had just returned to the Blue Jays after six weeks spent rehabbing an oblique injury, and he had just welcomed his wife and daughter to Toronto for some long-awaited family time during a long homestand. So Blue Jays general manager Ross Atkins' call informing him that he had been dealt to the Red Sox was politely but perhaps not altogether warmly received.

View Full Game Coverage

• Get World Series champions gear

:: World Series schedule and results ::

Atkins, though, put that early scheduling inconvenience into proper perspective for the man who had just been traded for the fourth time.

"Go win a World Series," he said.

The 35-year-old Pearce did just that on Sunday night, and his two-homer heroics in the Red Sox's 5-1 victory in the Game 5 clincher cemented his status not just as a World Series champion but as the Willie Mays World Series Most Valuable Player presented by Chevrolet.

"You know, baseball is a funny game," said Pearce, who finished the Fall Classic with three homers and eight RBIs. "You never know where the game will take you. And I've gone through a lot in my life or in my career to be here, and I couldn't be more thankful."

Pearce grew up a Red Sox fan in Florida ("brainwashed," as he once put it, by his Rehoboth, Mass.-born father, also named Steve), but that early rooting interest was not enough to compel him to join the club when he was drafted by Boston in the 10th round in 2004. He opted to go back for another season at the University of South Carolina before signing with the Pirates a year later after they plucked him in the eighth round.

Thus began a professional odyssey that would lead to a World Series oddity.

• Pearce homers twice as Sox surge to title

Video: WS2018 Gm5: Pearce homers twice to lead Red Sox

Before the Red Sox acquired him in a late-June trade that barely made a ripple in MLB headlines, Pearce played in the big leagues for the Pirates, Orioles, Blue Jays, Rays, Yankees and Astros. His arrival to Boston made him just the second player (joining Kelly Johnson) to play for every team in the American League East, and just the sixth to play for every team in any division.

Sunday's ceremony made Pearce just the second midseason acquisition (joining Donn Clendenon of the 1969 Mets) to win the Series MVP. In fact, Pearce is the first Series MVP, per the Elias Sports Bureau, with 50 or fewer career regular-season games played for his team.

When the Red Sox acquired Pearce from the Blue Jays this summer, manager Alex Cora described him as "one more weapon," and nobody knew then how weighty that weapon would be in the games that mattered most.

Video: WS2018 Gm5: Pearce on playing for Cora as manager

On a Red Sox team led by a duo of American League MVP Award candidates in Mookie Betts and J.D. Martinez, it was Pearce who came up with some of the biggest hits of the World Series. His homer off Clayton Kershaw gave Boston a 2-0 lead in the first inning on Sunday, and his solo shot off Pedro Baez made it 5-1 in the eighth.

Those homers came just a day after Pearce crushed a game-tying solo shot off Dodgers closer Kenley Jansen in the eighth inning of Game 4, followed by a three-run double off Kenta Maeda that broke the game open in the ninth.

All told, Pearce hit .333 (4-for-12), slugged 1.167 and scored five runs in this Series.

Video: WS2018 Gm5: Cora on Pearce's impact on Red Sox

It's a testament to this Boston team that the World Series MVP was no easy choice. David Price had an ample argument for the honor, having outpitched Hyun-Jin Ryu in Game 2 and been masterful for seven-plus innings in the clincher. Nathan Eovaldi might have been been an interesting choice, considering the value of his scoreless eighth innings in Games 1 and 2 and his bullpen-saving six-plus innings (regardless of end result) in Game 3.

But for what it's worth, Pearce led all Red Sox players in Win Probability Added for the Series, with a 0.6 mark (Price finished second at 0.4), per the Baseball Gauge.

Video: WS2018 Gm5: Pearce on Price's performance in playoffs

David Price was emotional after the Red Sox were crowned World Series champions

By Jessica Kleinschmidt
Oct. 28th, 2018

Perfect ending for near-perfect Red Sox

By Richard Justice MLB.com @RichardJustice
12:39 AM EDT

LOS ANGELES -- Take a long look at these Boston Red Sox as they celebrate winning yet another World Series, because you may not see a team as good as this one for a long time. This is perfection. Or as close to perfection as a team can get.

The Red Sox were a work of art from start to finish, and this magical season ended with them defeating the Dodgers, 5-1, in a clinching Game 5 of the 2018 World Series on Sunday night.

View Full Game Coverage

LOS ANGELES -- Take a long look at these Boston Red Sox as they celebrate winning yet another World Series, because you may not see a team as good as this one for a long time. This is perfection. Or as close to perfection as a team can get.

The Red Sox were a work of art from start to finish, and this magical season ended with them defeating the Dodgers, 5-1, in a clinching Game 5 of the 2018 World Series on Sunday night.

View Full Game Coverage

• Get World Series champions gear

:: World Series schedule and results ::

Sometimes, everything clicks. The Red Sox were brilliantly constructed and smartly managed. Their ownership is baseball's gold standard. Their on-field talent is off the charts.

Beyond those things, these Red Sox have a collective heartbeat that every player and coach identifies.

"There's just a closeness," World Series MVP Steve Pearce said. "It's hard to explain if you're not part of it."

• Pearce named World Series MVP

Where do the 2018 Red Sox rank among the all-time greats? That's a good debate for the offseason ahead. They won for the 119th time on Sunday. Only the 1998 Yankees (125) and the 2001 Mariners (120) won more games.

Boston's 108 regular-season victories were the most in franchise history and MLB's most since Seattle won 116 in 2001 (and then didn't get to the World Series).

The Red Sox finished eight games in front of a 100-win Yankees team, taking over first place in the American League East for good on July 2. They spent 141 of 186 days atop the division and were never more than two games out.

This final game -- four home runs and dominant starting pitching -- was a microcosm of an entire season. The Red Sox used every avenue to find talent, and all of it was on display at Dodger Stadium.

Video: WS2018 Gm5: Sale K's Machado, Sox win World Series

First, a salute to ownership. Everything changed for the Red Sox in late 2001, when a group headed by John Henry and Tom Werner purchased the franchise.

No longer would the Red Sox be the team that broke fans' hearts in October. Since they arrived, only the Yankees have won more regular-season games.

And their four World Series titles over the past 15 seasons are more than any other team (the Giants have won three).

Henry and Werner have hired smart people and given them the resources and freedom to do their jobs.

Video: WS2018 Gm5: Betts on winning his 1st World Series

This 2018 champions began to take shape with the development of homegrown talents like Mookie Betts, Xander Bogaerts, Jackie Bradley Jr. and Andrew Benintendi.

But the Red Sox also made smart trades and spent big on free agents when necessary. In a word, it's the model for every other team.

Few decisions were more important than the hiring of one of baseball's most respected executives, Dave Dombrowski, as president of baseball operations three years ago. It was his signing of slugger J.D. Martinez last spring that created a super lineup, and then his in-season trades for Pearce and Nathan Eovaldi were the finishing touches.

• Pearce homers twice as Sox surge to title

Video: WS2018 Gm5: Pearce homers twice to lead Red Sox

Game 5 of the World Series was a reflection of all the work. Three years ago, the Red Sox gave lefty David Price one of the largest free-agent contracts in history, and in the biggest start of his career, he allowed the Dodgers one run on three hits in seven-plus dominant innings.

Once the guy who supposedly couldn't win in October, Price had a spectacularly successful October. He appeared in three World Series games and performed well in all of them.

Price tapped his heart as he walked slowly off the mound in the eighth inning with the large contingent of Red Sox faithful at Dodger Stadium giving him a standing ovation he's likely to remember forever.

As for Pearce, he arrived via trade in June to deepen a lineup that was already the best in baseball. And he finished October with a home run and four RBIs in Game 4 and two home runs and three RBIs in the clincher to earn World Series MVP honors.

To some, Pearce seemed to be an unnecessary addition. His two-run homer off Dodgers ace Clayton Kershaw in the top of the first inning on Sunday got the Red Sox off to a fast start. Pearce added a solo shot in the top of the eighth.

Video: WS2018 Gm5: Statcast™ tracks Betts, J.D.'s late homers

Betts, the crown jewel produced by one of baseball's best Minor League systems, homered in the sixth, adding a line to a 2018 resume likely to include the AL Most Valuable Player Award.

When Dombrowski went looking for a new manager last offseason, he hired Astros bench coach Alex Cora. On his way to becoming the fifth rookie skipper to win a World Series, Cora became the prototype of the modern manager by building unshakable relationships with players.

And on a beautiful night in Southern California, it all fell into place for the Red Sox.

Richard Justice has been a reporter for MLB.com since 2011. Read his columns, listen to his podcast and follow him on Twitter at @RichardJustice.

Cora joins rookie managers who won World Series

By Andrew Simon and Matt Kelly MLB.com
Oct. 28th, 2018

When the Red Sox won their fourth World Series title in a span of 15 seasons with a 5-1 Game 5 victory over the Dodgers on Sunday night, Alex Cora became the fifth rookie manager in World Series history to win a championship.

Here is a look at the short list of rookie managers who prevailed in the Fall Classic. This exclusive club does not include Dallas Green (1980 Phillies) or Tom Kelly ('87 Twins), who won Fall Classics in their first full seasons as manager, but they had taken over as skipper midseason the year before.

View Full Game Coverage

When the Red Sox won their fourth World Series title in a span of 15 seasons with a 5-1 Game 5 victory over the Dodgers on Sunday night, Alex Cora became the fifth rookie manager in World Series history to win a championship.

Here is a look at the short list of rookie managers who prevailed in the Fall Classic. This exclusive club does not include Dallas Green (1980 Phillies) or Tom Kelly ('87 Twins), who won Fall Classics in their first full seasons as manager, but they had taken over as skipper midseason the year before.

View Full Game Coverage

Alex Cora, 2018 Red Sox
Cora joined the exclusive club with a five-game World Series victory over the Dodgers in his first season as the Red Sox's manager, a year removed from earning a ring as the Astros' bench coach in 2017. Prior to coaching with Houston, Cora played 14 seasons in the Majors from 1998-2011. He played for the Dodgers, Indians, Red Sox, Mets, Rangers and Nationals. Cora won a World Series title with Boston as a player in '07.

Bob Brenly, 2001 D-backs
A big league catcher for nine seasons, Brenly spent time as a coach with the Giants and then shifted into a role as a D-backs television analyst. That put him in position to move down to the dugout when expansion Arizona parted with its original manager, Buck Showalter, after backsliding from 100 wins to 85 in its third season, missing the playoffs.

Under Brenly, a D-backs club loaded with accomplished veterans such as Randy Johnson, Curt Schilling, Luis Gonzalez and Mark Grace rebounded to go 92-70 and win the National League West. Arizona got past St. Louis and Atlanta before winning a classic World Series against the Yankees on Gonzalez's walk-off bloop single against Mariano Rivera in Game 7. That was the peak for Brenly, who was let go in 2004 and returned to the broadcast booth.

Video: COL@ARI: Brenly tosses first pitch on Alumni Night

Ralph Houk, 1961 Yankees
Houk's career as a backup catcher consisted of 91 games for the Yankees over eight seasons, coincidentally playing under Bucky Harris (more on him below) in 1947-48. Houk found more success as a manager, after filling that role in the Minors and serving as a Yanks coach.

New York fired Hall of Fame skipper Casey Stengel after the 1960 team lost to Pittsburgh in Game 7 of the World Series, and it handed the reins to Houk. The cupboard was hardly bare, with the likes of Mickey Mantle, Roger Maris, Elston Howard and Whitey Ford helping Houk win 109 games. The Yankees beat the Reds in five games in the Fall Classic, and they repeated in '62 against the Giants. Houk managed 18 more seasons with the Yanks, Tigers and Red Sox, but he never won another championship.

Video: 1961 WS Gm5: Yankees win World Series

Eddie Dyer, 1946 Cardinals
Dyer was a middling pitcher for St. Louis before retiring in 1928 and joining Branch Rickey's revolutionary farm system and managing the Western Association's Topeka ballclub. Dyer continued managing ballclubs all over the eastern United States until finally getting the chance to skipper his former big league club in '46.

"I consider him the best judge of young players in the country," said Cardinals owner Sam Breadon of Dyer, "which I consider priceless at a time like this."

Dyer inherited a Cards club that had won three straight pennants from 1942-44, but the Redbirds fell behind the Dodgers early on in '45, dropping as far as 7 1/2 games back at the beginning of July. But St. Louis roared back to claim the NL lead within a span of three weeks, and ultimately prevailed over Brooklyn in a three-game tiebreaker at season's end to return to the World Series. Enos Slaughter completed his "mad dash" home to score the Series-winning run in Game 7, giving Dyer a title in his first year at the helm.

Video: MLB Productions looks back on the 1946 World Series

Bucky Harris, 1924 Senators
Washington's baseball club was often chided for being "first in war, first in peace and last in the American League" over its first several decades. In 1923, Senators owner Clark Griffith knew he needed to turn the tide, so he took a chance and made his 26-year-old second baseman, Harris, the team's player-manager.

The gamble couldn't have paid off any better. The "boy manager" piloted a team filled with stars -- including Hall of Famers Goose Goslin, Sam Rice and Walter Johnson -- to 92 wins and the franchise's first AL pennant, setting up a World Series matchup with the Giants in which Harris would play a major role. Not only did Harris hit .333 and knock two home runs, he also outmaneuvered the great John McGraw in Game 7 with a starting pitcher trick, and later brought in the aging Johnson for a heroic closing effort in the Senators' dramatic 12-inning victory.

Harris became the youngest manager to win the World Series in 1924, and he led the Senators back to the Fall Classic in '25 before falling to the Pirates in another seven-game set. Harris went on to win a World Series in his debut season with the Yankees in '47.

Matt Kelly is a reporter for MLB.com based in New York. Follow him on Twitter at @mattkellyMLB.

Andrew Simon is a research analyst for MLB.com. Follow him on Twitter at @AndrewSimonMLB.

Someone updated Steve Pearce's Wikipedia entry after his two Game 5 homers

By Chris Landers
Oct. 28th, 2018

Steve Pearce played hero for Boston in World Series Game 4 on Saturday night, launching a game-tying homer in the eighth to help the Red Sox escape with a 9-6 win. It was the sort of iconic moment that any player could hang his legacy on, let alone a 35-year-old journeyman.

Sox climb list of teams with most World Series titles

MLB.com
22 minutes ago

With their victory over the Dodgers in the 2018 World Series, the Red Sox secured their ninth championship, which tied them with the A's for the third most in baseball history.

Below is a breakdown of the eight teams with at least five World Series titles.

With their victory over the Dodgers in the 2018 World Series, the Red Sox secured their ninth championship, which tied them with the A's for the third most in baseball history.

Below is a breakdown of the eight teams with at least five World Series titles.

1. Yankees: 27
Years: 1923, '27, '28, '32, '36, '37, '38, '39, '41, '43, '47, '49, '50, '51, '52, '53, '56, '58, '61, '62, '77, '78, '96, '98, '99, 2000, '09

There is no other franchise in the Yankees' class when it comes to World Series titles. Not only are the Yanks the only team to win the World Series at least four times in a row, but they did it twice, winning four in a row from 1936-39, and five in a row from 1949-53. Not surprisingly, New York also holds the record for most World Series appearances (40).

Video: WS 2009 Gm 6: Yankees win their 27th title

2. Cardinals: 11
Years: 1926, '31, '34, '42, '44, '46, '64, '67, '82, 2006, '11

While they aren't close to the Yankees in terms of overall World Series titles, they are the class of the National League. St. Louis has maintained an impressive level of success even in non-World Series years, finishing with a record below .500 just once this century thus far.

Video: Must C Championship: Cardinals clinch 11th title

3 (tie). Red Sox: 9
Years: 1903, '12, '15, '16, '18, 2004, '07, '13, '18

Boston infamously went 86 years between titles thanks to the "Curse of the Bambino," but the Red Sox have come on strong in recent years, winning four titles in a span of 15 seasons from 2004-18. As a result, they are the first team to win four titles in the 21st century.

Video: WS2018 Gm5: Sale K's Machado, Sox win World Series

3 (tie). Athletics: 9
Years: 1910, '11, '13, '29, '30, '72, '73, '74, '89

The A's did much of their damage in the franchise's early years while they were still in Philadelphia, and then came on strong in Oakland after a brief stint in Kansas City from 1955-67. Along with the Yankees (1998-2000), they are one of two teams in the Divisional Era (which began in 1969) to win the World Series three times in a row (1972-74).

Video: 1989 WS Gm4: A's complete the sweep

5. Giants: 8
Years: 1905, '21, '22, '33, '54, 2010, '12, '14

The Giants are tied with the Dodgers for the most World Series appearances by an NL club (23), but they suffered a championship lull after moving to San Francisco prior to the 1958 season. They only appeared in the Fall Classic three times in their first 41 years out west, before winning it three times in five seasons to form a mini-dynasty under manager Bruce Bochy and catcher Buster Posey.

Video: Must C: Giants last team standing at the end of 2014

6. Dodgers: 6
Years: 1955, '59, '63, '65, '81, '88

The Dodgers have had most of their World Series success since moving to L.A. for the 1958 season, with five of their six titles coming on the West Coast. They were a frequent World Series participant when they are in Brooklyn, but went 1-8 in the Fall Classic while playing in their original home. With their loss to the Red Sox in the 2018 World Series, they now hold the distinction of having lost the World Series 14 times, most of any franchise (Yankees next at 13).

Video: 1988 WS Gm5: Dodgers win the World Series

7 (tie). Pirates: 5
Years: 1909, '25, '60, '71, '79

Pittsburgh is one of baseball's original franchises, and though the Pirates have made just seven World Series appearances in their history, they have made them count. Their .714 winning percentage in the World Series (5-2) is the best of any of the teams that have made the World Series more than twice.

Video: '79 WS, Gm7: Pirates defeat the Orioles, 4-1

7 (tie). Reds: 5
Years: 1919, '40, '75, '76, '90

Cincinnati hasn't come close to the World Series since shocking the A's with a four-game sweep in 1990, but the Big Red Machine is arguably most dominant squad in the history of the NL, and the Reds hold the distinction of being the last NL team to repeat as champion.

After World Series loss, Kershaw opt-out decision nears
Oct. 28: Clayton Kershaw gave up four runs on seven hits over seven innings in the Dodgers' 5-1 loss to the Red Sox in Game 5 of the World Series on Sunday, Los Angeles' second World Series defeat in as many years. The three-time National League Cy Young Award winner and former NL Most Valuable Player now faces a decision on whether to opt out of the remaining two years on his contract. He has three days following the end of the World Series to do so.

Kershaw, 30, is owed $65 million over the next two seasons should he choose not to opt out. But he could also opt out to test the free agency market, making the Dodgers choose whether or not to meet or exceed the bids of other potential suitors. 

"I haven't made the decision yet," Kershaw said following the World Series loss. "We have three days to talk, between us and the Dodgers, see what happens. And then we'll go from there."

Kershaw has arguably been the greatest starting pitcher of his generation. But injuries have taken their toll in recent years, particularly back issues. The left-hander hasn't made more than 27 starts in four of the last five seasons, and the velocity on his fastball has diminished significantly. He has had mixed results in his postseason career, adding a 4.20 ERA this October to his record.

Has Harper already made his choice?
Oct. 28: Bryce Harper will be the most watched free agent of them all this offseason, as the 26-year-old slugger hits the open market for the first time. Given his age, and the fact that he already has a National League Most Valuable Player Award on his shelf, along with six All-Star selections, Harper could command a hefty contract. He has reportedly said he's willing to start with figures of 10 years and $350 million. But does he already have his mind made up as to where he wants to sign?

Harper's agent, Scott Boras, spoke with Michael Kay on the YES Network on Sunday, and Kay asked him directly about where Harper would sign. In what appeared to be a tongue-in-cheek response, after which he and Kay joked and chuckled, Boras said "we know who the team is, it's already completed and done. But Bryce has told me he wants to tell you personally." After the statement, Kay responded with, "That was such a tease ... you got me excited for a second."

Tweet from @YESNetwork: Will Scott Boras reveal where his client Bryce Harper plans on signing this offseason? 🤔 pic.twitter.com/mlyPzsynqT

Whatever the status of Harper's impending free agency is at the moment, it will be followed closely as free agency officially begins 10 days after the World Series ends. Harper has had big seasons -- including his MVP campaign in 2015 -- but his production declined in 2018, when he hit .249/.393/.496 with 34 homers. His OPS dropped by 119 points from an injury-shortened 2017 season (111 games).

Price opt-out still appears unlikely even with strong postseason
Oct. 28: David Price's last three playoff starts have been excellent -- six scoreless innings to beat the Astros in the Red Sox's clinching Game 5 win in the ALCS, followed by six innings of two-run baseball to beat the Dodgers in Game 2 of the World Series, and capped off with seven strong innings in Boston's 5-1 World Series-clinching victory in Game 5. But a strong October run might not be enough to convince the left-hander to opt out of the four years and $127 million remaining on his contract with Boston.

According to the New York Post's Joel Sherman, there's still a "strong expectation" that Price won't opt out, because the 33-year-old wouldn't be able to match or exceed the amount remaining on his deal as a free agent.

Price would be taking a sizable risk if he opted out. His current contract has an average annual value of $31.75 million over the next four years. He might also have difficulty finding a more attractive landing spot from an on-field standpoint, with Boston seemingly poised to contend for the life of his contract.

When a reporter from masslive.com asked him about his intentions in September, for example, Price replied, "Why would I leave here to go to a team that's not as good as this team? I came here to win. I don't worry about all the other stuff. Just come here to win. We're going to have a really good chance to do that."

Kelly bolsters free agency candidacy with stellar postseason
Oct. 28: Reliever Joe Kelly struck out the side in a perfect eighth inning against the Dodgers in Boston's 5-1 Game 5 victory to win the World Series on Sunday night. It capped a strong postseason performance for the flamethrowing right-hander, who finished with a 0.79 ERA in nine appearances (11 1/3 innings), striking out 13 and walking none.

Kelly, 30, took a step back during the regular season, posting a 4.39 ERA over 73 appearances after a 2017 campaign in which he had a 2.79 ERA in 54 appearances for Boston. As he heads into free agency this winter, his postseason success may bolster his value on the relief pitching market.

Oct. 28: Cole Hamels posted a 2.36 ERA with 74 strikeouts and 23 walks over 12 regular-season starts for the Cubs after the Rangers traded him to Chicago in late July. The performance made a great impression with the club, and according to MLB Network insider Jon Heyman in an article for Fancred Sports, the Cubs "will surely pick up the $20 million option" on the veteran left-hander's contract, instead of buying him out for $6 million. Hamels, 34, will be entering his 14th Major League season in 2019, with a 3.40 career ERA.

Blue Jays may not pick up option on Smoak
Oct. 28: Though he posted an .808 OPS with 25 homers over 147 games for Toronto in 2017, Justin Smoak's $7 million club option may not be picked up, according to MLB Network insider Jon Heyman in an article for Fancred Sports. Nunez will likely exercise option with Sox
Oct. 28: Eduardo Nunez, who has had an eventful World Series to say the least, will likely exercise his $5 million option with the Red Sox this offseason, reports MLB Network insider Jon Heyman in an article for Fancred Sports. Nunez didn't have a strong season at the plate in 2018, hitting .265/.289/.388 with 10 homers in 127 games. His OPS dropped from .801 in '17, to .677 this year. During the World Series, he has had some big hits, including a three-run homer in a Game 1 victory over the Dodgers at Fenway Park, and an infield single that resulted in the tying run scoring in Game 3, an 18-inning marathon that the Red Sox lost, 3-2.

Eovaldi had dominant postseason, but will there be a cost?
Oct. 28: Nathan Eovaldi's October was an impressive showcase in advance of his free agency this winter. The Red Sox right-hander was brilliant again in Game 3 of the World Series, even though he ended up taking the loss in the 18th inning.

Originally scheduled to start Saturday's Game 4, Eovaldi was called into action in the 12th inning of Game 3 and proceeded to turn in one of the best relief performances in postseason history. He threw six innings of two-hit baseball, allowing only one unearned run, before Max Muncy finally got to him for the walk-off home run in the bottom of the 18th at Dodger Stadium.

Video: WS2018 Gm3: Eovaldi goes 6-plus in admirable outing

Eovaldi might well be pitching himself into one of the biggest contracts of any free-agent starting pitcher this year. He now has a 1.61 ERA this postseason across his two starts and four relief appearances. Factor in his young age (28) and elite stuff (headlined by triple-digit heat), and Eovaldi looks like one of the top starters on the market.

One interesting question, though, is whether Eovaldi's postseason efforts might be a double-edged sword. Yes, he's been dominant. But he's also pitched a heavy workload -- he threw 97 pitches on just one day of rest in his Game 3 relief outing, after pitching in both of the first two games of the series -- and he's just coming off his second career Tommy John surgery. Eovaldi was a major contributor to Boston's World Series championship, but the long-term health of his arm will certainly be a key factor for teams looking to sign him.

What will Giants do about their GM vacancy?
Oct. 27: The Giants' search for a general manager has extended to nearly a month, and whether or not they make a hire before the GM Meetings begin on Nov. 5 remains uncertain. As one of the other teams that had been seeking a new GM now looks ready to make its hire -- the Mets, who are negotiating with Brodie Van Wagenen -- what will the Giants do about their own vacancy?

The Giants have shown interest in Cubs vice president of scouting and player development Jason McLeod and MLB senior vice president of baseball operations Kim Ng, as well as Brewers GM David Stearns, though Milwaukee owner Mark Attanasio declined San Francisco permission to speak with Stearns.

McLeod, who has been with the Cubs throughout the Theo Epstein era since joining the club in 2011, is signed with the Cubs through 2021. Prior to joining Chicago, McLeod spent six years in Boston's scouting department and joined current Cubs GM Jed Hoyer when Hoyer left to take the GM position with the Padres from the 2010-11 seasons.

At MLB, Ng has overseen international operations and talent development. Ng previously worked for the Dodgers as vice president and assistant to then GM Ned Colletti, and has also held front office roles with the White Sox and Yankees. She's reportedly interviewed for GM roles with the Dodgers, Mariners, Padres and Angels.

The Giants' front office vacancy opened when former general manager Bobby Evans was dismissed last month. It appears possible that president of baseball operations Brian Sabean and team president Larry Baer could carry the team's search into the GM Meetings, potentially using the Meetings as an interview platform.

When the club requested to interview Stearns, MLB Network insider Ken Rosenthal reported that the club had been seeking for Stearns to fill the role of president of baseball operations, which currently held by Sabean. That could leave open the possibility that Sabean may be reassigned within the front office depending on who the club hires to replace Evans and to what position.

Pearce joins ranks of unlikely World Series heroes

By Matt Kelly and Do-Hyoung Park MLB.com
Oct. 28th, 2018

Red Sox first baseman Steve Pearce was the hero of Boston's World Series-clinching 5-1 Game 5 victory over the Dodgers in Los Angeles on Sunday night, marking the latest unlikely hero to shine in the Fall Classic.

And that's the beauty of October baseball: As has been shown countless times, anyone can play the role of hero in the World Series, from future Hall of Famers to the 25th man on the roster. Here's a look back at some unlikely heroes who made their marks on Fall Classics in recent history.

Red Sox first baseman Steve Pearce was the hero of Boston's World Series-clinching 5-1 Game 5 victory over the Dodgers in Los Angeles on Sunday night, marking the latest unlikely hero to shine in the Fall Classic.

And that's the beauty of October baseball: As has been shown countless times, anyone can play the role of hero in the World Series, from future Hall of Famers to the 25th man on the roster. Here's a look back at some unlikely heroes who made their marks on Fall Classics in recent history.

Steve Pearce, 2018 Red Sox
Pearce launched a pair of home runs in Boston's title-clinching victory over the Dodgers in Game 5, securing the World Series Most Valuable Player Award. The first homer was a two-run shot off Clayton Kershaw to give the Red Sox an early lead. He then belted another home run in the eighth, this one a solo shot off Dodgers reliever Pedro Baez. It was his third home run in two days, after he came through with a game-tying blast in Game 4 before breaking the game open on a bases-clearing double in the ninth. Boston acquired pearce in a trade with Toronto in late June, and he wound up hitting .289 with a pair of doubles and four homers in the postseason. That included a .333 performance (4-for-12) with a double and three homers in the World Series.

David Freese, 2011 Cardinals
There was, of course, someone all too familiar with unexpected World Series heroics watching Nunez's blast from the Dodgers' dugout Tuesday night. Freese wasn't fully established as an everyday player in 2011, his third season in the Majors, but he started every playoff game for the Cardinals -- and singlehandedly changed the course of the World Series and cemented his place in baseball lore. In Game 6, with the Rangers a strike away from a championship, Freese tagged Texas closer Neftali Feliz for a game-tying two-run triple that sent the game to extra innings. Then he led off the 11th with a walk-off homer that sent the series to a Game 7. Freese followed that less than 24 hours later with a two-run double and a pair of walks in that Game 7 to be crowned World Series MVP.

Video: Must C Classic: Freese's walk-off shot forces Game 7

Carlos Ruiz, 2008 Phillies
Though he was one of the game's more respected backstops in his prime for the Phillies, Ruiz struggled mightily at the plate in 2008, his second full season in the Major Leagues, slashing a meager .219/.320/.300 while splitting time behind the plate with veteran Chris Coste. But Ruiz played a pivotal role in the Phils' postseason success, hitting .313 with a pair of multihit games in the National League Championship Series before he delivered the heroics in Game 3 of the World Series against the Rays. Ruiz knocked the only walk-off infield single in World Series history in that game. He hit safely in the last four games of the World Series and guided the Phillies' pitching staff to a 2.86 ERA in the Fall Classic.

Video: 2008 WS Gm3: Phillies win on Ruiz single

David Eckstein, 2006 Cardinals
On a team that featured the likes of Albert Pujols, Scott Rolen, Jim Edmonds and Chris Carpenter, it was light-hitting infielder Eckstein who claimed the World Series MVP Award. Despite collecting only 21 extra-base hits in 500 at-bats during the regular season, Eckstein helped push the Cardinals past the Tigers in Game 4 with three key doubles as part of a 4-for-5 performance. He hit an RBI double in the third to drive in St. Louis' first run, then doubled to lead off the seventh before scoring the game's tying run. In the eighth, with the game knotted 4-4, Eckstein came through one more time off Tigers reliever Joel Zumaya with a go-ahead, two-out RBI double that pushed the Cards to a 3-1 series lead.

Scott Podsednik, 2005 White Sox
Despite his blazing speed on the basepaths (he led the NL with 70 steals during 2004), Podsednik only hit one triple during the '05 regular season for the White Sox. And though he'd displayed a bit of a power stroke in two seasons with the Brewers, he didn't muster a single homer in 2005 before the playoffs began. But a different Podsednik emerged in the World Series against the Astros. After driving in a key insurance run in Game 1 with an eighth-inning RBI triple, he muscled a walk-off homer in Game 2 off Astros closer Brad Lidge, who had saved 42 games during the regular season. Podsednik added another triple in Game 4 and finished second on the White Sox in hits during their World Series sweep of Houston.

Video: WS 2005 Gm 2: Podsednik hits a walk-off homer

Francisco Rodriguez, 2002 Angels
It's not even fair to call the 20-year-old K-Rod of 2002 a "rookie" -- he didn't even make his Major League debut until Sept. 18 due to a rash of injuries to the Angels' bullpen. But in his five regular-season appearances, he showed manager Mike Scioscia that his electric right arm could be a critical factor in the playoffs -- and Scioscia didn't hesitate to use his newfound weapon early and often in October. Rodriguez struck out 15 in 10 innings over seven appearances in the AL Division Series and ALCS before throwing 8 2/3 innings in four World Series outings, including three perfect innings in Game 2 and a scoreless eighth in Game 7, when he struck out the side to set up closer Troy Percival and the only championship in Halos history.

Luis Sojo, 2000 Yankees
The turn-of-the-millennium Yankees dynasty completed its championship three-peat with a five-game triumph over the Mets in 2000, and in the clinching Game 5, it was Sojo, a journeyman infielder who sealed the Subway Series win for the Yanks. After being double-switched in during the eighth inning to hit in Andy Pettitte's lineup spot, Sojo brought in Jorge Posada with the Series-winning run in the top of the ninth; a second, insurance run scored on the play due to a throwing error. Sojo also played in the '01 World Series with the Yankees and had four plate appearances in 2003 before his Major League career came to an end.

Video: 2000 WS Gm5: Sojo's single gives Yanks lead

Pat Borders, 1992 Blue Jays
It's hard to fathom that a 1992 Blue Jays team loaded with offensive stars like Roberto Alomar, Joe Carter, John Olerud, Devon White and Dave Winfield would combine to hit just .230 in a World Series. But Toronto's offense largely struggled against Braves pitching and likely wouldn't have pulled out the franchise's first title without unlikely contributions from its catcher. Borders, a .242 hitter during the regular season, racked up a team-best nine hits and hit .450 en route to Series MVP honors. He went on to play for nine other franchises in a 10-year span after leaving Toronto in the winter of '94.

Video: WS1992 Gm4: Borders hits a solo home run off Glavine

Mickey Hatcher, 1988 Dodgers
Yes, this Series is known first and foremost for Kirk Gibson -- but Gibson won the 1988 NL MVP Award before he injured his legs in the NLCS against New York. Hatcher, meanwhile, homered in Games 1 and 5 of the Fall Classic after going deep just once over 202 plate appearances in the regular season. The outfielder finished the series with a .368 average and five RBIs in the Dodgers' huge upset of the A's.

Video: WS1988 Gm5: Hatcher hits second home run of series

Rick Dempsey, 1983 Orioles
Needless to say, Dempsey was not the hitter circled in the Phillies' 1983 World Series scouting report, as the catcher hit .231 with four homers over 400 plate appearances during the regular season. But after going 2-for-12 in the ALCS against the White Sox, Dempsey came alive, hitting .385 in the Fall Classic with all five of his hits going for extra bases (four doubles and one homer). Dempsey earned Series MVP honors, but did not make a single All-Star team over 24 big league seasons.

Brian Doyle, 1978 Yankees
Series MVP Bucky Dent could have just as easily been selected here, but Doyle was just as much a hero out of left field for a Yankees team filled with stars. An infielder who finished his career with a .161 average over 110 regular-season games, Doyle filled in for injured second baseman Willie Randolph and hit .438 (7-for-16) with the second and third RBIs of his career in the Yanks' six-game win over the Dodgers. His first RBI came in New York's ALCS triumph over the Royals.

Video: WS1978 Gm6: Brian Doyle extends lead with RBI single

Gene Tenace, 1972 A's
Tenace's 82 regular-season appearances for the A's in 1972 constituted his career high at the time, and he batted just .225 with 13 extra-base hits (five homers) for the AL champs. He was dreadful in the ALCS, going 1-for-17 with an RBI single during Oakland's five-game squeaker over the Tigers. But something flipped in Tenace during the World Series, as the catcher hit .348 (8-for-23) with four homers and nine RBIs to capture Series MVP honors over bigger A's stars like Vida Blue, Rollie Fingers, Ken Holtzman and Catfish Hunter.

Video: BB Moments: '72 WS, Gm 7: Gene Tenace, Unlikely Hero

Donn Clendenon, 1969 Mets
Clendenon won the 1969 World Series MVP despite the fact that he was a healthy scratch in Game 3. He didn't make a single appearance in the Mets' NLCS victory over the Braves and didn't even wear a New York uniform until he arrived via a trade from the Expos in mid-June. But the first baseman made the most of his limited playing time, recording at least one hit in each of his four World Series starts and knocking homers in Games 2, 4 and 5. The Mets squeaked out 2-1 victories in two of the three games in which Clendenon went deep.

Video: WS Gm5: Clendenon hits his third home run of series

Don Larsen, 1956 Yankees
Would you have picked a pitcher who was 30-41 lifetime, had lost 21 games for the Orioles two years prior and was shelled in a game prior in the Series (four runs in 1 2/3 innings in Game 2) to throw the first and only perfect game in Fall Classic history? Larsen's Game 5 masterpiece still ranks among the biggest surprises in World Series history, with the image of catcher Yogi Berra jumping into Larsen's arms ranking as one of its most enduring. Larsen pitched in 14 Major League seasons without an All-Star Game selection and finished his career with an 81-91 record.

Video: 1956 WS Gm5: Don Larsen tosses a perfect game

Johnny Podres, 1955 Dodgers
Podres went 9-10 for the Dodgers in 1955, his third season in the Majors, and might have been his team's fourth-best starter that year behind Don Newcombe, Carl Erskine and Billy Loes. But it's hard to imagine the Dodgers finally beating the Yankees and winning their only title in Brooklyn without Podres. The southpaw earned the first World Series MVP Award after holding the Yanks to three runs in a complete-game effort in Game 3 when his team was down two games to none and then firing a shutout in Game 7 at Yankee Stadium.

Video: 1955 WS Gm7: Dodgers win their first World Series

The Red Sox blasted 'New York, New York' in the clubhouse after winning the World Series

By Chris Landers
12:26 AM EDT

You may remember that, a few weeks ago, Aaron Judge celebrated a win over the Red Sox in ALDS Game 2 by blaring "New York, New York" as he walked out of Fenway Park.

The Red Sox, for their part, definitely remember. How do we know? Because, after winning the World Series at Dodger Stadium on Sunday night, they took the celebration back to the clubhouse ... and knew exactly what song to fire up.

The latest Harper free-agent rumors

MLB.com
Oct. 28th, 2018

After a seven-season tenure with the Nationals that included a National League Rookie of the Year Award in 2012, an NL MVP Award in 2015 and six All-Star nods, Bryce Harper is set to become a free agent for the first time.

Below, you will find a list of the latest news and rumors surrounding the outfielder.

After a seven-season tenure with the Nationals that included a National League Rookie of the Year Award in 2012, an NL MVP Award in 2015 and six All-Star nods, Bryce Harper is set to become a free agent for the first time.

Below, you will find a list of the latest news and rumors surrounding the outfielder.

Has Harper already made his choice?
Oct. 28: Bryce Harper will be the most watched free agent of them all this offseason, as the 26-year-old slugger hits the open market for the first time. Given his age, and the fact that he already has a National League Most Valuable Player Award on his shelf, along with six All-Star selections, Harper could command a hefty contract. He has reportedly said he's willing to start with figures of 10 years and $350 million. But does he already have his mind made up as to where he wants to sign?

Harper's agent, Scott Boras, spoke with Michael Kay on the YES Network on Sunday, and Kay asked him directly about where Harper would sign. In what appeared to be a tongue-in-cheek response, after which he and Kay joked and chuckled, Boras said "we know who the team is, it's already completed and done. But Bryce has told me he wants to tell you personally." After the statement, Kay responded with, "That was such a tease ... you got me excited for a second."

Tweet from @YESNetwork: Will Scott Boras reveal where his client Bryce Harper plans on signing this offseason? 🤔 pic.twitter.com/mlyPzsynqT

Whatever the status of Harper's impending free agency is at the moment, it will be followed closely as free agency officially begins 10 days after the World Series ends. Harper has had big seasons -- including his MVP campaign in 2015 -- but his production declined in 2018, when he hit .249/.393/.496 with 34 homers. His OPS dropped by 119 points from an injury-shortened 2017 season (111 games).

Yankees' free-agent preference: Harper or Machado?
Oct. 25: After finishing eight games behind the rival Red Sox in the American League East and then losing to them in the ALDS, the Yankees could be gearing up for an offseason of blockbuster moves as they look to close the gap.

The Yankees' 2018 payroll put them under the luxury-tax threshold, which means they won't be subject to repeat-offender rates if they cross the threshold in 2019. As a result, a major spending-spree can't be ruled out. But considering New York's biggest priority is upgrading the rotation, the club is unlikely to come away with both Manny Machado and Bryce Harper, the top two free-agent hitters. If the Yankees can choose only one, MLB.com's Bryan Hoch expects it to be Machado.

New York has a greater need in the infield, with shortstop Didi Gregorius potentially set to miss most of the 2019 season following Tommy John surgery and Miguel Andujar having an uncertain future at third base due to his defensive shortcomings.

Even if they decline Brett Gardner's $12.5 million club option (with a $2 million buyout), the Yankees still have Aaron Judge, Giancarlo Stanton, Aaron Hicks, Jacoby Ellsbury, Clint Frazier and No. 2 prospect Estevan Florial as potential outfield options in 2019. More >

Do Phillies have preference between Machado and Harper?
Oct. 24: The Phillies are expected to pursue both Manny Machado and Bryce Harper in free agency this offseason, but it will likely be difficult to land both, given the competition for each player and the size of their projected contracts.

There was a time when Machado may have been the preferred choice between the two, as several members of the Phillies' front office have ties to the Orioles, with whom Machado played from 2012-18 before being traded to the Dodgers in July.

But according to MLB.com's Todd Zolecki, Machado's recent proclamation to MLB Network insider Ken Rosenthal in an article for The Athletic that he isn't "the type of player to that's going to be 'Johnny Hustle'" could give the Phillies some pause, knowing their fan base's affinity for gritty players.

"I think some of the stuff that happened during the NLCS with Manny Machado has maybe turned a total slam dunk, 'We're definitely going to go for him, we have no hesitation going for him and giving him $300-plus million,' I think it's now something that they have to think a little bit harder about," Zolecki said.

"If the Phillies could pick one or the other, and they knew the guy was going to be productive over the next 10 years or so, I think they would probably take Bryce Harper … I think he's just one notch above Manny Machado in terms of sheer star power."

Video: Zolecki on Phillies' pursuit of Machado and Harper

Braves unlikely to make bids for Harper, Machado
Oct. 19: While the Braves may have at least $60 million to address their multiple needs, which include a catcher, a corner outfielder, bullpen depth and a frontline starter, they may take a cautious approach to the free-agent market to avoid deals that hinder them down the road.

"We're not going to just walk in the store and buy because we have money in our pockets," Braves general manager Alex Anthopoulos said. "If we don't find the right deal with something we like, there's still other opportunities to shop. There could be opportunities next season. If you start signing guys to big, long deals, if you feel good about the deal, you do it now. I wouldn't force a deal right now that would limit you in years from now."

As a result, the Braves are unlikely to make competitive offers for Bryce Harper or Manny Machado. Rather, the club is more likely to be aggressive on the trade market as it looks to take another step forward after winning the National League East in 2018.

"I don't think with our club, with what we have, that the value is going to be there in the free-agent market," Anthopoulos said. "It doesn't mean it won't. We'll certainly explore it. But if I could sit here in the middle of October, I'd say it's more likely we go the trade route. It's not ideal to give up young assets, but it's also not ideal to do a deal you don't believe in -- that may look good for a year or two, and then in years three, four and five, it does not." More >

Nats planning to make strong effort to retain Harper
Oct. 18: As fan bases and front offices around the Majors dream of having Bryce Harper in the fold next season, the only team Harper has ever played for is holding out hope that the impending free agent will be back.

According to MLB Network insider Jon Heyman in an article for Fancred Sports, the Nationals plan to make a strong effort to retain Harper this offseason, though they are also formulating an alternative plan in case he opts to sign elsewhere.

This comes after Chelsea Janes of the Washington Post reported last week that the consensus within the Nats organization is that the club does not want to eclipse the competitive balance tax threshold after doing so in each of the past two seasons.

If Harper is signed for roughly $30 million annually, it could considerably hinder the Nationals' ability to address other needs on the roster. However, it doesn't sound like that will prevent Washington from making a major push to re-sign its homegrown star.

Janes also reports that if Harper signs, it could mean center fielder Adam Eaton goes on the trade block. Eaton has only played in 118 games during two seasons with Washington due to injury, hitting .300/.394/.422.

Phillies set to make run at Harper, Machado
Oct. 18: Will Bryce Harper and Manny Machado join forces in Philadelphia? According to MLB Network insider Jon Heyman in an appearance on "The Rundown" on Thursday, the Phillies are prepared to pursue both players, and many expect them to come away with at least one.

"People around baseball are going to be surprised if [the Phillies] don't get at least one of these two players, and maybe both," Heyman said.

Heyman had a similar report back in September, writing for Fancred Sports that multiple rival executives believed that the Phillies could land both superstars.

However, as Heyman pointed out Thursday, it could ultimately be tough for any team to pull that off, as both players are looking to break the bank in free agency. Furthermore, any club looking to sign either player will have plenty of competition.

Video: Heyman on Mariners, Phillies free agent rumors

Will Yankees chase Harper, Machado in effort to catch up to Red Sox?
Oct. 11: After spending much of the season chasing the Red Sox in the American League East and then losing to Boston in the ALDS, the Yankees will be looking to close the gap with their offseason moves.

One way they could do it? A spending spree that results in Bryce Harper and Manny Machado wearing pinstripes, as Newsday's Anthony Rieber wrote Wednesday.

That type of plan isn't as outrageous as it sounds, especially after the Yankees stayed under the luxury-tax threshold in 2018 -- which means they won't be subject to the repeat-offender penalty next season. Without that restriction, the Yankees will likely look to significantly increase their payroll.

Of course, the rotation is arguably a greater area of need for New York than the offense, with Luis Severino struggling in the second half and CC Sabathia, J.A. Happ and Lance Lynn hitting free agency. Adding a starter such as Patrick Corbin, who is expected to be one of the Yankees' free-agent targets, according to a report from MLB Network insider Jon Heyman, may be the club's top priority.

Rizzo: Harper 'in our plans' for future
Sept. 30: Nationals general manager Mike Rizzo confirmed Sunday before the season finale that the club wants impending free agent Bryce Harper back.

"Of course he's in our plans," Rizzo said. "He's a guy we would love to have. He's a part of our family. He's a big part of this roster, performance-wise. Like I've always said with these type of deals, you're not betting on the baseball player, you're betting on the person. He's a person we'd like to have with us."

Rizzo's comments came in response to Harper saying he would "absolutely love to be" with the Nats long term, provided the club was interested in re-signing him.

"Am I in the [Nationals'] plans, you know? I don't know," Harper said. "It's hard to think about ... It's like, 'Well, it could all be over in a second.' It's kind of crazy.

"I've always said, 'If I'm in those plans, I'd absolutely love to be here.' But if I'm not, there's nothing I can do about it. There's nothing I can do. I would love to play next to Victor Robles or Juan Soto or Adam Eaton. I'd love to. But am I in those plans? I have no idea." More >

Harper expresses desire to remain with Nats
Sept. 25: As Bryce Harper prepares to become a free agent for the first time this offseason, the outfielder told the Washington Post that he would "absolutely love to be" in Washington long term.

"I think about other cities, but I love it here," Harper said.

"When I talk about D.C., I get giddy. I get happy. Because it's me. It's what I know," Harper said. "I don't know anything else. I don't know what it feels like to play for the Dodgers. I don't know what it feels like to play for the Yankees. I don't know what it feels like to play for anybody that you look at." More >
